              <h5 class="card-title">Peak Flow Logs</h5>
              <p class="card-body">
                Medications and Treatment: Asthma medications are divided into
                two main categories: Long-term control medications: Inhaled
                corticosteroids, long-acting beta-agonists, and leukotriene
                modifiers Quick-relief medications: Short-acting beta-agonists
                and anticholinergics What to Do in the Event of an Asthma
                Attack: If you or someone you know experiences an asthma attack,
                follow these steps: Stay calm and sit upright to facilitate
                breathing Use your quick-relief inhaler (usually a short-acting
                beta-agonist) as prescribed by your doctor Wait for 5-10 minutes
                to see if your symptoms improve If there's no improvement or if
                your symptoms worsen, call emergency medical services
                immediately Follow your asthma action plan and inform your
                healthcare provider of the situation Additional Resources:
                Asthma and Allergy Foundation of America (AAFA): www.aafa.org
                American Lung Association: www.lung.org Centers for Disease
                Control and Prevention (CDC) - Asthma: www.cdc.gov/asthma Global
                Initiative for Asthma (GINA): www.ginasthma.org Remember,
                managing asthma is a lifelong process. Educate yourself, follow
                your action plan, and communicate with your healthcare provider
                to maintain a healthy and active life.
              </p>
